The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Infotech acquires Geospace Integra

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Hyderabad, May 15: Hyderabad-based Infotech Enterprises has acquired Geospatial Integrated Solutions. 

 The companies provide software packages on geographical information to various utilities, telecom and transportation firms and government departments.

 The market for these services in India and West Asia is worth Rs 1,000 crore and is expected to grow 12 per cent in the next five years. 

 Large-scale mapping initiatives by the government are unlocking geospatial opportunities in several areas. These include land records; urban planning; environment, forestry and natural resources; utility infrastructure planning and management; and defence. 

 Under the terms of the agreement, Infotech and Geospace Integra will consolidate their geospatial business in India and West Asia into a single entity led by Chandrasekhar Nori, chairman and managing director of Geospace Integra. 

 The new entity will operate as a subsidiary of Infotech. B.V.R. Mohan Reddy, chairman and managing director of Infotech, said: In our effort to reinforce our leadership position in the global geospatial markets, India and West Asia have become increasingly strategic to our growth objectives.

 By leveraging the knowledge and experience of Geospace Integra, supported by Chandrasekhar Noris leadership, we can offer a compelling value proposition for customers in these markets, he added.

 We expect to achieve Rs 100 crore revenue in the next three years from our businesses in India and West Asia.

 Nori said, Im excited about joining hands with Infotech Enterprises.




